    "explanation": "In the late 1980s, i.e., during 1985–90, the annual growth rates of basic industries and capital goods industries were 7.4% and 14.8% respectively, which were higher than the annual growth rate of consumer goods industries (7.3%). Therefore, in this period, Indian industry clearly reflected the desired trend of structural shift, reversing the structural regression of 1965–80 (in which the production structure changed in favour of the capital goods industry necessary for long-term industrial development). Due to the expansionary fiscal policy adopted by the Government of India in the 1980s—such as large budget deficits year after year, excessive government borrowing, and an increase in dissaving—income increased; consequently, demand for consumer goods also increased. This is clear from the fact that in the Seventh Five-Year Plan, the per capita income growth rate was 3.7% per year, higher than earlier plans. Further, while the growth rate of consumer goods industries was about 5–6% and 6.7% per year during 1974– 79 and 1980–85 respectively, it was about 7–8% per year during 1985–90. Hence, the reason is incorrect.\nSource: 40th B.P.S.C. (Pre) 1995",
